    "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
    "body": "I don't see - how we can make 1 response field optional (without giving to client any signal). \r\n\r\nHere is what popular Databases/Cache return as error responses:\r\n\r\n- Redis error response:\r\n```\r\nERROR\\r\\n \r\n<error_message>\\r\\n \r\n```\r\n\r\n- MySql error response:\r\n```\r\n0xFF <error_message>\r\n```\r\n\r\n- Postgres error response: \r\n```\r\nE <error_message>\r\n```\r\n\r\n- Memcached error message: \r\n```\r\nERROR\\r\\n\r\nor\r\nCLIENT_ERROR <error_message>\\r\\n\r\nor\r\nSERVER_ERROR <error_message>\\r\\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo, we may follow the same approach - encode `ResponseOk/ResponseError` constants as the first field of all responses. Then clients depends on received status will execute different decoding logic. It will give us flexibility to add new response type in future (for example `ClientError`).\r\n\r\n",
